The evolution of gear can unlock greater effectiveness for the end-user. While skill still beats gear, it's undeniable that gear still matters a lot. The latest evolution of the Sidecar does just that thanks to it's modular design. It unlocks more options that allow you to build exactly what you need to maximize your preparedness.

node.text:
Skill > Gear. It’s something we’ve been saying for years. So when it comes to getting the latest and greatest Sidecar holster… no you don’t absolutely have to upgrade. The Legacy Sidecar still gets you from point A to B. We know that’s not going to stop you from getting that new-new, but it’s important to remember that skill still beats gear. Focus on what matters most.
-
#trexarms #trexarmskydex #sidecar #holster

Our Rifle Basics Class is available, for free, at TREX-ARMS.com.
Advanced shooting is all about mastering fundamentals and this 3 hour video captures Lucas breaking it down for a class of students. Check it out, take notes, and make a personal plan for improvement. This release also marks the launch of our new Training page, complete with a video archive of previous training videos, printable targets, drills, weapon and gear loadouts, and more.
And we're still just getting started...
-

Taking one class a year and using it to gather homework that you can use to improve on your own time is way more valuable than taking class after class after class and never really improving that much. Over the years, we have stressed the importance of personal education followed up with hard work and consistent practice. Eventually though, we all run into the problem of plateauing and that's where classes come in.
-
This year Lucas took a private class with @Joel.Park_ of @Practicalshootingtraininggroup and collected a lot of things he can be working on, which is what you're seeing here.
-
#trexarms #trexarmskydex #highstandards

Candela is the measurement of directional light and is often a better way to determine what a flashlight is actually doing. High candela creates focused hot spots like on the @modlitesystems OKW and are very blinding and push light a really long way. When working inside though, that hot center can create a lot of shadows at whatever you are not lighting up. Options like the @surefire_llc M600 are often more flexible inside because of the "flood" of light that it throws. Though there are several great options for weapon lights on the market (Modlite, Surefire, Streamlight) finding what will work best given the environments you commonly find yourself in is crucial.
-
#trexarms #trexarmskydex #highstandards

Shoot: Find the threat, engage the threat and keep your rifle loaded. 
Move: Advance in the desired direction while staying safe.
Communicate: Keep your buddy up to date on what's going on and what you need.

Shooting is something we all strive to do well, moving and communicating are both done on a daily basis but can become complex when in gear and with radios. Still, they are all basic civilian tasks that should be practiced together. Keep it simple and execute cleanly.
-

node.text: As the sun set this day twenty years ago, many were still pulling people out of ruble. In just a few hours it would be a new day, September 12th, and we awoke with a renewed sense of resolve. And while much has changed since then, for better and for worse, we must not forget that preserving innocent life and caring for one another is a calling that can unite us all. It did twenty years ago and it can still today.

node.text:
If you're hitting up an Airsoft or other training event, be sure to run your gear as close as possible to how your rifle/kit is set up in "real life". The whole point is to test yourself and your gear, so taking shortcuts by removing your plates or lightening your loadout pretty much defeats the purpose. This goes for how you run your gear as well, as it would be easier/faster to shoot an airsoft gun without aiming down your optic, but you'd be losing out on getting reps and seeing through your optic and how it performs in different lighting and environments. Don't game it, even though it's a game. Hold yourself to a higher standard.⁠
-⁠

-⁠

node.text:
The gun community/firearms industry is pretty toxic. We see it every day. The reality is; every industry/profession where money and fame exists will result in toxic individuals and behaviors. Bitterness. Jealousy. Cutthroat competitiveness. Slander. You name it. The question is; what can we do to be the opposite?
-
This past weekend, we took a team out to American Milsim’s Copperhead event in Playas, NM. 600 players outfitted in kit, airsoft guns, NODs, going head-to-head for two days. Military, LE, and citizens all involved. Another company attended as well; @haleystrategicofficial . Travis Haley brought out a bunch of his guys to interact with folks and partake in the battle.
-
I’m incredibly thankful Travis and his guys came out. While we both run competitive companies in this industry, and have had our differences in the past; we put all that aside for something more important: spending time with people and inspiring future gun-owners. He and I also spent hours chatting together about all sorts of things beyond guns and this industry.
-
Our community needs people who prioritize a significant mission over money, fame, and dopamine.
-

What you carry, is just as important as how you carry it. A backpack with medical items at the bottom of the bag isn't going to help much. Mags carried in inconsistent ways are not going to offer you much consistency in reloads. Finally, slings that snag or inhibit movement can cause just as much problem as having no sling at all. Weapon light activation should be seamless. Your brain says “light on” and your light turns on. With minimal lag between the decision from your brain to your manipulation with finger or thumb. A lot of people treat their weapon lights as accessories, not vital parts of the gun they subconsciously use. You’ll never have quality subconscious performance thinking of lights just as “add-ons”.

1.93 optic mounts are slick. Especially once you combine helmets. On occasion I’ve had my helmet tip forward shooting in a weird position and the helmet edge blocks some of my scope while using a standard-height mount. A 1.93 keeps your head angled upright which helps prevent blockage. There’s other benefits including comfort and better stock placement. Pictured is a Vortex Razor 1-6 HD II in a Geissele 1.93 mount.
